Scott: The only reason I think you wouldn't want it to be is because the genius of it shines when you have the understanding of a trick-taking game and you see how this is a twist on that formula.

619
00:38:09,780 --> 00:38:12,305
Scott: And it's sort of like you can appreciate it, right?

620
00:38:12,345 --> 00:38:20,000
Scott: Whereas if you could just play this, never having taken a trick in your life, but you wouldn't have a full appreciation for what they've done here.

621
00:38:22,381 --> 00:38:23,342
Scott: So how does this game work?

622
00:38:23,383 --> 00:38:24,044
Scott: It's really simple.

623
00:38:24,484 --> 00:38:30,473
Scott: There's a deck of cards, numbered one through nine, and every number, there are five copies.

624
00:38:30,634 --> 00:38:33,678
Scott: So five ones, five twos, five nines, right?

625
00:38:33,698 --> 00:38:34,680
Scott: There's forty-five cards.

626
00:38:34,900 --> 00:38:34,996
Scott: Yep.

627
00:38:35,742 --> 00:38:38,220
Scott: And you deal out the cards to all the players.

628
00:38:39,040 --> 00:38:41,211
Rym: It's very important to note, these cards are all the same.

629
00:38:41,252 --> 00:38:42,156
Rym: All the fives are the same.

630
00:38:42,176 --> 00:38:42,860
Rym: They're all just black.

631
00:38:43,281 --> 00:38:44,102
Scott: Yeah, there's no suits.

632
00:38:44,322 --> 00:38:47,646
Scott: It's just numbered one through nine, just deal out the cards.

633
00:38:48,568 --> 00:38:55,978
Scott: And you deal them out, and everyone now has a hand, and everyone picks a card to sort of get rid of, right?

634
00:38:56,038 --> 00:38:57,620
Scott: They just throw it out of the game, basically.

635
00:38:58,740 --> 00:39:01,523
Scott: Let's say I have a one in my hand, and I throw it out.

636
00:39:01,583 --> 00:39:07,009
Scott: Well, now I know that there's only four ones left in the game total, right?

637
00:39:07,049 --> 00:39:17,300
Scott: Because there were five, there could be even less than four, but I know that there are less than five ones available in the total deck because I threw one out, right?

638
00:39:18,121 --> 00:39:22,467
Scott: Okay, and then you start playing a trick-taking game, a very normal trick-taking game.

639
00:39:22,507 --> 00:39:31,980
Scott: You play a card, everyone has to follow suit, whoever has the highest in that suit wins, unless someone didn't have that suit, in which case they can play a different suit.

640
00:39:32,701 --> 00:39:35,725
Scott: If they played the Trump suit, then they would win, right?

641
00:39:35,885 --> 00:39:46,539
Scott: Even against someone who had... It's just basic trick-taking game, nothing weird about it whatsoever, completely normal, not one weird rule at all.

642
00:39:46,800 --> 00:39:46,980
Scott: None.

643
00:39:47,441 --> 00:39:50,548
Scott: No special anything, the red suit is Trump.

644
00:39:51,330 --> 00:39:55,680
Scott: But wait, didn't you just say that all the cards are all black, there's no suits on them?

645
00:39:55,840 --> 00:40:04,020
Rym: Well, when you play a card, you play it on a little cardboard thing in front of you, and you decide what its suit is at the moment you play it.

646
00:40:04,581 --> 00:40:07,926
Scott: Right, so I play a five, and I say, "This five is

647
00:40:08,647 --> 00:40:08,968
Scott: yellow.".

648
00:40:09,108 --> 00:40:09,789
Scott: I decided it.

649
00:40:09,989 --> 00:40:16,279
Scott: When I play it, at the moment I play it, I decide I can pick any suit I want, and I say, "It's five, yellow, it's

650
00:40:16,299 --> 00:40:16,560
Scott: yellow.".

651
00:40:17,000 --> 00:40:25,176
Scott: And what I do when I do that is I take a little marker, and there's a board, and the board has 45 slots on it, one for every card.

652
00:40:25,597 --> 00:40:27,400
Scott: And I put a marker on the yellow five.

653
00:40:28,061 --> 00:40:31,847
Scott: Now, someone else might have a five in their hand, and they might want to play it.

654
00:40:32,569 --> 00:40:34,612
Scott: Well, they can, no problem.

655
00:40:34,732 --> 00:40:39,360
Scott: They just can't say it's yellow, because, well, the yellow five already got played.

656
00:40:39,520 --> 00:40:46,811
Rym: Because remember, the name of this game, fully, is Cat in the Box, and then subtitle, Quantum Trick-Taking Game.

657
00:40:46,891 --> 00:40:53,480
Rym: Because the rule is, you can only play one real card, meaning a yellow five, there's only one yellow five.

658
00:40:53,600 --> 00:40:57,734
Rym: You can't play a card that has already been played, the combo of number and color.

659
00:40:58,015 --> 00:40:59,500
Rym: It's a riff on Schrodinger's Cat.

660
00:41:00,320 --> 00:41:00,481
Scott: Yep.

661
00:41:01,202 --> 00:41:03,647
Scott: So, everyone goes around playing a trick-taking game.

662
00:41:03,667 --> 00:41:05,290
Scott: So, I play a yellow five, right?

663
00:41:05,330 --> 00:41:06,793
Scott: Well, now it's Rym is to the left of me.

664
00:41:06,813 --> 00:41:10,220
Scott: Alright, so Rym, I guess he has to follow suit.

665
00:41:11,222 --> 00:41:14,113
Scott: So, if he plays a two, he's gotta say yellow.

666
00:41:14,133 --> 00:41:15,237
Scott: He can't be like, "Red

667
00:41:15,338 --> 00:41:15,418
Scott: two.".

668
00:41:15,980 --> 00:41:19,853
Rym: Well, I could be red two, but I have to then first say, "Oh, no!

669
00:41:20,275 --> 00:41:21,138
Rym: I'm out of yellow!

670
00:41:21,158 --> 00:41:21,599
Rym: That

671
00:41:21,639 --> 00:41:21,840
Rym: sucks!".

672
00:41:22,322 --> 00:41:27,660
Rym: And then I take a marker off my board, showing that I'm, quote, "out of yellow," and I play some other suits.

673
00:41:27,660 --> 00:41:34,540
Scott: Which means that for the rest of that round, Rym can never play another yellow card, because he said he didn't have any yellows left.

674
00:41:35,801 --> 00:41:41,110
Rym: If I desuit myself by just declaring I've desuited, I am tied to that for the rest of the hand.

675
00:41:41,350 --> 00:41:47,100
Rym: And if it turns out that yellow is literally the only play I have left for one of my cards, I'm just effed.

676
00:41:47,821 --> 00:41:49,043
Scott: Right, so that's the final thing.

677
00:41:49,584 --> 00:41:59,320
Scott: You play cards, you decide the suit when you play them, and when you decide the suit, you can only choose a suit for that card that hasn't been played by any other player.

678
00:42:00,001 --> 00:42:05,400
Scott: And you can't choose a suit if you have already declared yourself to be desuited in that, right?

679
00:42:06,101 --> 00:42:18,300
Scott: And then, if someone is in a position where all the cards remaining in their hand have no legal play, then that person has caused a paradox, and they lose, and they get boned, and they lose points.

680
00:42:20,700 --> 00:42:23,828
Scott: Otherwise, everyone gets a point for every trick they took.

681
00:42:25,071 --> 00:42:28,980
Scott: At the beginning of each round, you can bid on how many tricks you think you're gonna take.

682
00:42:29,302 --> 00:42:31,279
Rym: But your options are just like one, two, or three.

683
00:42:31,900 --> 00:42:32,942
Scott: Yeah, you can't, right?

684
00:42:32,982 --> 00:42:35,146
Scott: So if you go over three, that doesn't matter.

685
00:42:35,507 --> 00:42:43,020
Scott: But if you hit exactly the bid that you made, then you get bonus points equal to these markers on this.

686
00:42:43,600 --> 00:42:57,480
Rym: So, basically when you play the yellow five, and you put the marker on yellow five, and say later you play a yellow six, or a blue five, or whatever's next to it on that marker board orthogonally.

687
00:42:59,720 --> 00:43:09,760
Rym: Your bonus points, if you hit your bid, are the total number of your markers that is largest of a contiguously orthogonally adjacent set.

688
00:43:10,240 --> 00:43:15,740
Rym: So if I make a big blob of like eight of them, daddy eight points, and I probably definitely won the entire game, because that's nuts.

689
00:43:15,840 --> 00:43:25,100
Scott: Right, but it's like you have an incentive to pick colors, you know, suits, such that your markers on the board are orthogonally adjacent.

690
00:43:25,260 --> 00:43:27,768
Scott: So you want to make runs in the same suit.

691
00:43:27,888 --> 00:43:31,680
Scott: You want to be like, I played the yellow four, and the yellow five, and the yellow six.

692
00:43:31,900 --> 00:43:38,780
Scott: Or you also want to pick, right, like I played the yellow four, and the blue, well there's two, there's the easy side of the board.

693
00:43:38,800 --> 00:43:43,160
Rym: I was about to say, there's that easy baby mode, and there's a really good mode.

694
00:43:43,581 --> 00:43:51,800
Scott: In the baby mode, everything's lined up, so you can just be like blue four, yellow four, green four, right, blue five, and make a blob that way.

695
00:43:52,181 --> 00:43:58,100
Scott: But in the hard mode, everything's offset a little bit, so you can still make runs like three, four, five in the same suit.

696
00:43:58,561 --> 00:44:04,080
Scott: But if it's like, you want to be like blue two, yellow three, green four, that would make a vertical column.

697
00:44:05,482 --> 00:44:11,320
Rym: So the only other rule, and just standard trick taking rule, you can't lead the trump suit unless it's been broken.

698
00:44:11,541 --> 00:44:11,983
Rym: Like that's it.

699
00:44:12,264 --> 00:44:15,520
Rym: And that's a totally normal, that's not a gotcha, that's just a regular old trick taking thing.

700
00:44:15,780 --> 00:44:16,220
Rym: Like trick taking 101.

701
00:44:16,220 --> 00:44:19,820
Scott: And that's the whole game, you play several rounds, you lose the most points, the end.

702
00:44:20,660 --> 00:44:21,563
Rym: And it's great.

703
00:44:23,027 --> 00:44:27,200
Rym: Of the two games we played, I came in second place by one point in the first game, and I won the second game.

704
00:44:27,801 --> 00:44:30,111
Rym: But I don't think that was my, the first game.

705
00:44:30,131 --> 00:44:32,260
Rym: that was luck, but I do have some heuristics.

706
00:44:32,400 --> 00:44:38,120
Rym: Like there is some skill here, and I think play can evolve based on what I noticed in the two games we played.

707
00:44:38,662 --> 00:44:42,233
Scott: I am ashamed to admit it took me several games to learn.

708
00:44:42,534 --> 00:44:44,400
Scott: the most basic fact is, right?

709
00:44:44,600 --> 00:44:46,439
Scott: And so I'm going to teach it to you so you don't fuck it up.

710
00:44:46,781 --> 00:44:49,259
Rym: Oh, then I'll teach the thing I figured out in game two.

711
00:44:49,940 --> 00:44:53,440
Scott: This is so simple and obvious, I should have figured it out as soon as I heard the rules.

712
00:44:53,580 --> 00:44:55,339
Scott: It took me several games to understand this.

713
00:44:55,921 --> 00:44:59,040
Scott: That there are five copies of any number in the deck, right?

714
00:44:59,680 --> 00:45:02,815
Scott: And you can only, so there are five fours, right?

715
00:45:03,197 --> 00:45:03,740
Scott: In the whole deck.

716
00:45:04,881 --> 00:45:10,500
Scott: If four fours get played, obviously the fifth one can never be played, otherwise trouble.

717
00:45:11,281 --> 00:45:23,420
Scott: If you start in your opening hand and you've got more than one four or more than one two, and you take one of them and throw it out at the start, then you know the other one is perfectly safe.

718
00:45:23,740 --> 00:45:27,440
Scott: You can always, as long as you don't desuit yourself and stupidly, right?

719
00:45:28,022 --> 00:45:31,580
Scott: You'll know that you can safely play that other one, right?

720
00:45:31,801 --> 00:45:46,211
Scott: So if you draw in your opening hand like three threes, obviously you should probably throw away one of the threes, and now you know for sure those other two threes are safe, and you can just sort of hold them till the end of the round, and you won't paradox that way.

721
00:45:46,473 --> 00:45:47,580
Scott: Try to get all the other cards.

722
00:45:47,680 --> 00:45:52,760
Scott: If you've got like one four in your opening hand, okay, keep it, but try to play it quickly.

723
00:45:53,281 --> 00:46:09,680
Scott: That way you can get it out, and if no one else is thrown away at four, and there's a dangerous paradoxical four out there, at least it's not in your hand, and I paradoxed often when I started playing, and once I understood this, I stopped paradoxing basically.

724
00:46:09,860 --> 00:46:13,535
Rym: I only paradoxed once, and it was a negative zero paradox.

725
00:46:13,615 --> 00:46:14,720
Rym: I was okay on that one.

726
00:46:17,022 --> 00:46:26,518
Rym: So my slightly more advanced heuristic that worked so well is kind of like when you showed how you were winning citadels, and everyone was like, "Oh fuck, that's why Scott was

727
00:46:26,538 --> 00:46:26,720
Rym: winning.".

728
00:46:26,720 --> 00:46:27,406
Scott: Mine wasn't even a heuristic.

729
00:46:27,426 --> 00:46:29,099
Scott: It was just like a basic fact.

730
00:46:30,122 --> 00:46:31,309
Scott: It was so simple.

731
00:46:31,329 --> 00:46:33,320
Scott: I don't know how I didn't understand that from game one.

732
00:46:33,400 --> 00:46:53,460
Rym: My baby heuristic that is the sole reason I won that second game and will definitely not work again was, whatever number every single player played first, unless there was like a weird situation with like, you know, like someone leads something really high first round, whatever they play, I assumed they were trying to get rid of it because they have more than one in their hand.

733
00:46:54,982 --> 00:46:59,540
Scott: No, you would get rid of it early because you don't have more than one in your hand.

734
00:47:00,601 --> 00:47:07,760
Rym: Well no, meaning they have more than one in their hand after throwing stuff away, and they're trying to get rid of the most dangerous card in their hand.

735
00:47:08,520 --> 00:47:12,199
Scott: But if you have multiple numbers of a card in your hand...

736
00:47:12,360 --> 00:47:14,700
Rym: Say you have two fours in your hand after you threw stuff away.

737
00:47:15,260 --> 00:47:16,800
Scott: But I would have thrown away one of the fours.

738
00:47:16,800 --> 00:47:20,720
Rym: What if you have three fours and three ones when you have to decide what to throw away?

739
00:47:20,800 --> 00:47:21,880
Scott: That's really weird.

740
00:47:24,224 --> 00:47:25,639
Rym: I had draws like that every game.

741
00:47:27,462 --> 00:47:31,400
Scott: The other thing is that when you get to the end of the round, you don't play your final card.

742
00:47:31,980 --> 00:47:33,800
Scott: So really you can save two cards.

743
00:47:33,980 --> 00:47:44,004
Scott: So if I had three ones and three fours, I would throw away a one at the start, or maybe throw away a four at the start, and then one of the ones, I would just sort of say, "This is the card.

744
00:47:44,025 --> 00:47:45,636
Scott: I'm not going to play this round no matter

745
00:47:45,677 --> 00:47:45,858
Scott: what.".

746
00:47:46,281 --> 00:47:56,060
Scott: And now I know that the ones and the fours are all safe to play, and I would put those also, deprioritize playing those, and try to get all the other cards played first.

747
00:47:56,424 --> 00:47:57,118
Scott: I went harder.

748
00:47:57,280 --> 00:47:58,840
Scott: Because I know that those are the dangerous and risky ones.

749
00:47:58,880 --> 00:48:05,225
Rym: Because the fact that if someone paradoxes the hand ends immediately, I won the second game.

750
00:48:05,526 --> 00:48:14,940
Rym: because every time someone paradoxed, almost every time I would have been forced to paradox if it got around to me, but someone paradoxed before, I aggressively tried to make someone paradox.

751
00:48:15,562 --> 00:48:15,871
Rym: Oh yeah.

752
00:48:16,420 --> 00:48:17,878
Rym: And the way I would do that is...

753
00:48:18,020 --> 00:48:21,340
Scott: Especially, the turn order matters a lot too, especially on the final round.

754
00:48:21,500 --> 00:48:24,559
Scott: Like if you can see, because everyone's going to deal one hand, right?

755
00:48:25,240 --> 00:48:34,580
Scott: So if you say, "Okay, I'm the first dealer in the first round, and then that means on the last round, I will be going second.

756
00:48:35,061 --> 00:48:37,858
Scott: And so I'm probably relatively

757
00:48:37,939 --> 00:48:38,120
Scott: safe."

758
00:48:38,140 --> 00:48:41,040
Scott: Because you're not going to paradox before the last round unless you're really bad, right?

759
00:48:41,202 --> 00:48:42,400
Rym: It happened a couple times though.

760
00:48:43,022 --> 00:48:46,740
Rym: You can just get screwed by the colors or like being forced to desuit or something.

761
00:48:46,780 --> 00:48:50,800
Scott: It's possible, but it's like on that final round, it's like, "Okay, I'm going to be going second.

762
00:48:50,920 --> 00:49:00,379
Scott: I'm kind of safe, but I can obviously be in a position of power to really hurt the third or fourth

763
00:49:00,419 --> 00:49:00,760
Scott: players.".

764
00:49:01,081 --> 00:49:10,055
Scott: If I look at that board on that final turn, and I see that three threes have been used, and I've got the fourth three, it's like, "I'll play

765
00:49:10,076 --> 00:49:10,297
Scott: that.".

766
00:49:10,720 --> 00:49:13,316
Scott: And it's like, "All right, it can't be a three.

767
00:49:13,457 --> 00:49:13,759
Scott: What do you

768
00:49:13,779 --> 00:49:13,900
Scott: got?".

769
00:49:14,502 --> 00:49:21,160
Rym: So what I did, and this was super effective just saying in these early games, I don't think it'll last because obviously this is easily defeated.

770
00:49:21,840 --> 00:49:26,316
Rym: Whoever in the first hand, whatever number, I look at all the numbers.

771
00:49:26,356 --> 00:49:27,560
Rym: everyone who did not lead played.

772
00:49:28,381 --> 00:49:35,800
Rym: I pick one of those players, especially if I have one or two of that number, and I do the same thing like pushing spades and hearts.

773
00:49:36,301 --> 00:49:45,520
Rym: I play that number at my next opportunity to try to force them into a corner by getting to the point where I hope they had two threes, let's say, they got rid of one.

774
00:49:46,361 --> 00:49:50,040
Rym: I force other threes out to try to get to the point to where all four threes are taken up.

775
00:49:50,322 --> 00:49:51,879
Rym: So now they've got a liability in their hand.

776
00:49:52,620 --> 00:49:59,960
Scott: I mean, filling up a number in general is going to create the most dangerous situation for someone.

777
00:50:02,202 --> 00:50:06,240
Rym: So I would try to keep two of a number, which is highly risky, like two fives.

778
00:50:06,722 --> 00:50:10,760
Rym: Someone plays a five, I play a five, my next two cards are fives, just trying to fuck them over.

779
00:50:10,820 --> 00:50:14,520
Scott: Well, if you have two fives and you haven't shoved one under at the start, right?

780
00:50:14,561 --> 00:50:15,460
Rym: I would keep one sometimes.

781
00:50:15,560 --> 00:50:20,700
Scott: It's like, right, well it's like, you know that if you keep one of them to the end, you're safe.

782
00:50:21,000 --> 00:50:26,700
Scott: But if you can play both, then you know you've definitely probably put the hurt on somebody.

783
00:50:26,860 --> 00:50:31,280
Rym: Exactly, and I played this game both times the same way I play hearts.

784
00:50:31,781 --> 00:50:39,120
Rym: I don't try necessarily to minimize my score so much as I try to fuck over other players and force them into bad situations.

785
00:50:40,041 --> 00:50:42,240
Rym: And that's just how I often play trick-taking games.

786
00:50:42,420 --> 00:50:45,580
Rym: And it's highly effective in two plays of this game.

787
00:50:45,620 --> 00:50:51,040
Scott: I think the worst draw in this game would actually be like three pair, right?

788
00:50:51,180 --> 00:50:55,019
Scott: Because you, let's say, got two twos, two threes, two fours.

789
00:50:55,521 --> 00:50:59,920
Scott: I can hide a two at the start, I can save a three at the end.

790
00:51:00,362 --> 00:51:04,120
Scott: It's like, well I've got two fours and I have to play them both, right?

791
00:51:04,300 --> 00:51:08,220
Rym: If I had that situation, I would aggressively desuit early on purpose.

792
00:51:08,340 --> 00:51:11,376
Rym: Which, you remember, I desuited way early and everyone was like,

793
00:51:11,436 --> 00:51:12,099
Rym: "Whoa!"

794
00:51:12,241 --> 00:51:13,138
Rym: And I won, so.

795
00:51:14,121 --> 00:51:17,160
Scott: But it's like, I would try, I would play those fours, right?

796
00:51:17,240 --> 00:51:23,459
Scott: I would try to play them quickly so that, you know, because there's a risk that there could be five of them out there.

797
00:51:23,861 --> 00:51:29,840
Rym: In that situation, if I had like three pairs, I would aggressively desuit to try to get them all out on purpose.

798
00:51:30,200 --> 00:51:39,620
Rym: Because, early, quickly, because if you have those cards and you're playing with the skewed board, then that lines up into an extremely orthogonally adjacent pile of points.

799
00:51:39,904 --> 00:51:40,879
Rym: That is worth the risk.

800
00:51:42,462 --> 00:51:46,580
Rym: You can have like a seven, eight, nine point hand and that'll probably win you the whole thing.

801
00:51:46,660 --> 00:51:47,458
Rym: It's worth going for it.

802
00:51:48,087 --> 00:51:49,040
Rym: Of course, if you paradox!

803
00:51:50,240 --> 00:51:59,800
Scott: The problem is desuiting too early, you might end up hurting yourself because it's like, okay, I know for sure that there are, I ditched a one at the start and I've got a second one.

804
00:52:00,161 --> 00:52:02,400
Scott: And I know there's only four ones out there, right?

805
00:52:02,942 --> 00:52:05,320
Scott: And I desuit, you know, in blue or something.

806
00:52:05,780 --> 00:52:08,479
Scott: And then everyone gets played except the blue one.

807
00:52:09,321 --> 00:52:12,920
Scott: And I'm the only, this is the only one that's left because I ditched one of them.

